Stack Memory Layout During Execution
Higher Addresses
[rbp+24] Arg 9
[rbp+16] Arg 8
[rbp+8] Arg 7
[rbp] Return Address (8 bytes)
Pushed by CALL instruction
[rbp-8] Saved RBP
Pushed in prologue
[rbp-16] Local var 1
[rbp-24] Local var 2
[rbp-32] Local var 3
Lower Addresses (RSP here)
Function Call with 7+ Arguments (System V AMD64 ABI)
Caller prepares arguments
Arguments 1-6
RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
Arguments 7+ pushed on stack
(right to left order)
call function
Pushes return address
Jumps to function entry
Function prologue:
push rbp
mov rbp, rsp
sub rsp, N (local space)
Function body executes
Access args via registers/[rbp+offset]
Access locals via [rbp-offset]
Function epilogue:
mov rsp, rbp
pop rbp
ret
Return to caller
Pop return address into RIP
RAX contains return value
